  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Doctors should be cautious in prescribing aspirin
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   to prevent heart attacks until more research supports its value.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Studies do indicate that aspirin reduces the risk of first non- fatal heart attacks,
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   by reducing the ability of blood platelets
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   to form clots.
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   But for people who have
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   clotting problems or have high blood pressure aspirin may increase the risk for hemorrhagic stroke.
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   In one study, there were 10 hemorrhagic strokes recorded among the 11,000 subjects taking aspirin,
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   compared with 2 strokes in the 11,000 taking a substitute.
  </a>
  <a href="#10" id="10">
   Overall death rates for the two groups were similar,
  </a>
  <a href="#11" id="11">
   though the aspirin non-fatal heart attack rate was much lower.
  </a>
